bib_record.title: Measurement and analysis of the energy-angular distribution of secondary neutrons for 9Be at 5.9 and 6.4 MeV incident neutrons

free_txt: 4.5 MV Van de Graaff accelerator TOF
facility in the Institute of Heavy Ion Physics,
Peking University.
The secondary neutron detector consisted of a
105 mm diameter x 50 mm thick ST-451 liquid
scintillator (similar to NE213) directly coupled to
an XP2040 photomultiplier tube.
A Stilbene scintillator (40 mm diam. 25 mm thick)
directly coupled to a RCA8575 photomultiplier tube was
employed as a monitor to measure the intensity and
spectrum of source neutrons in TOF mode, and used
for neutron fluence normalization for the
measurements at different angles for a certain
incident energy.
The experimental uncertainty was estimated by
considering the contributions from:
counting statistics (2-12%),
detector efficiency (2.2-4%),
absolute normalization (3-4%),
sample size correction (2-8%).
4.5 MV Van de Graaff accelerator TOF
facility in the Institute of Heavy Ion Physics,
Peking University.
The monoenergetic neutrons with energies of
5.9 and 6.4 MeV were produced via the d + D reaction
using a deuterium gas target. target. The cell of
gas target is a tantalum-lined stainless-steel
cylinder of 10 mm long x 9.5 mm o.d. isolated from
the vacuum system by a 5.0 mu-m thick molybdenum foil
and filled to a pressure of 2.8 atm with 99.9% high
purity deuterium gas.
The beryllium scattering sample was a right cylinder
of 40 mm high and 30 mm outside diameter.
